Faction.name: Grand Order of the Reiksguard Knights
{=H5iWxbbl}Spirit Seekers
Faction.text: {=4TiYXBqK}The Spirit Seekers are a band of mercenaries who recruit from the tribes of southern Arabya and the lands to the east. They are legally their own slaves and masters: each “sells“ himself to the order and, in the process, becomes a part-owner. They are known for their fine horses and fine clothes. But no one should assume from their oiled locks, perfumes and peacock feathers that they spend more time preening then training. Their skills as mounted archers are second to none, and as lancers are close behind the Brettonian, Wood Elves and the imperial cataphracts.

Faction.name: {=LqTTchsa}Grudgebringers
Faction.text: {=bhxVA9w7}Named after the magical sword of former Commander Morgan Bernhardt, this Dogs of War mercenary group lives off its former glory.

Faction.name: {=7k9izAvC}Norscan Hunting Pack
Faction.text: {=bsPd5zri}The Hunting Pack, or Shield Brothers, are a Norscan Dogs of War company for those who take fighting and training very seriously. They are primarily Varg but do allow recruits from other tribes, as long as an already-serving Shield Brother will vouch for them. Their rules are almost monastic: no women in their encampments and no amusements, and no Brother is allowed to spend the night outside without permission.

Faction.name: {=UmVjzPI4}Leopold's Leopard Company
Faction.text: {=tae3lhXh}Leopold's Leopard Company was once a famous band of Dogs of War mercenaries that had's its origins within the great city-state of Luccini. The Leopard Company takes its name from the legendary Leopard of Luccini, which is a badge and the mascot of the city's rulers. It is said that this Leopard was a guardian of the divine twins Lucan and Luccini, founders of the city from time long ago. Since then, the company has fallen on hard times.

Faction.name: {=nh4Y3LOc}Wild Wood Elf Kindred
Faction.text: {=7bhNgOKd}These wild wood elf kindred groups are heirs to a long tradition in the Athel Loren lands wherein great warriors went “wilding” for part of their youth, learning the ways of the woods and how to suffer hardship. So long as these elves wear no sewn clothes, eats no cooked food, and sleeps under no roof, he is immune from the laws of men. In fact, wildlings tend to be the youths of noble families taking a few years to indulge their feral side, robbing travellers and living viciously and not necessarily hewing to the old code.

Faction.name: {=as2TiAIJ}Bowmen of Bergerac
Faction.text: {=xahrUc5n}The Bowmen of Bergerac started as a Brettonian peasant movement, hiding out in the forests, robbing from the rich and giving to the poor. However, it encountered the problems that any long-running rebel movement might – it needed to ensure a steady supply of food, and also ensure that none of the poor would dare earn a bag of coins by informing on them. Slowly but surely, it began to make use of extortion, terror, and corrupt deals with the local authorities to survive, becoming little different from any other organized bandit group in the Old World.

Faction.name: {=MVHawAEp}Cult of Slaneeshi
Faction.text: {=nQOf27Rx}The Chaos God Slaneesh can find many ways to infiltrate the uncorrupted and worm its way into the hearts and minds of men, elves and dawi. These cultists have surrended to the god of excess, offering themselves to the Ruinous Power of pleasure and pain. They work to bring down the kingdoms of order from within.

Faction.name: {=7WL1LWdf}Southern Border Princes
Faction.text: {=9ZEdEWmi}The Border Princes, the free people, live on the badlands at the edge of the Empire. Originally the descendants of runaway slaves and debtors, they soon became highly valued by the local imperial commanders for their knowledge of this frontier zone. Their leaders have been granted titles, their young men taken into the retinues of archons and emperors. But though they are now very loyal to the idea of the Empire, they remain quite hostile to its actual authority.

Faction.name: {=mtZu1l2j}Cult of Tzeentch
Faction.text: {=B8c2mNKj}The Chaos God Tzeentch can find many ways to infiltrate the uncorrupted and worm its way into the hearts and minds of men, elves and dawi. These cultists have surrended to the god of divine mystery, offering themselves to the Ruinous Power of Change. They work to bring down the kingdoms of order from within.

Faction.name: {=8ba4tpRU}Arabyan Roamers
Faction.text: {=RWOYui01}The Roamers are the main bedouin confederacy in the Nahhas desert. They wander from highland to lowland grazing grounds, declaring huge swathes of the desert their “territory” in which any caravan must offer protection money. They compose poems of their deeds and mock other clans of the Banu Asera for having given up the “freedom” of black wool tents for stone houses in the oases. The other clans consider them boastful nuisances, though grudgingly respecting them as protectors of the old Aserai ways.

Faction.name: {=6BvGhzao}Kurgans
Faction.text: {=XJbDRBfd}The Kurgans are a nomadic clan that has resisted all efforts by the Norscan and Greenskin tribes to keep them in one place, give them farmlands and serfs, and force them to give over taxes and military levies. They are treated by the other clans with a combination of envy and contempt. They trade and sometimes even intermarry with their settled brethren, but they also do a limited amount of kidnapping for ransom and raiding of flocks, and scoff at those who would blame them for carrying on with the heroic old ways.

Faction.name: {=o7ud4X2X}Forest People
Faction.text: {=0u8ipbgn}The tribes known as the Forest People practice slash-and-burn farming in the deep woods, outside the grasp of the Norscan boyars. They burn down tracts of trees, grow crops on the virgin soil fertilized by ash for a few years until the land is exhausted, and move on. It is an inefficient use of land but a very efficient use of labor, suitable for a numerically small population in a large area. Also, because the plots are hard to measure and tax, it's a very good strategy for people who don't care to be governed.

Faction.name: {=eC6qIOzz}Northern Border Princes
Faction.text: {=9qAWNBvA}The Border Princes, the free people, live on the badlands at the edge of the Empire. Originally the descendants of runaway slaves and debtors, they soon became highly valued by the local imperial commanders for their knowledge of this frontier zone. Their leaders have been granted titles, their young men taken into the retinues of archons and emperors. But though they are now very loyal to the idea of the Empire, they remain quite hostile to its actual authority.
